        { "type": "range", "id": "answer_size", "label": "Answer text size", "min": 10, "max": 20, "step": 1, "default": 13 },
        { "type": "text", "id": "q_1", "label": "Question 1", "default": "My baby keeps throwing the spoon. Is that normal?" },
        { "type": "textarea", "id": "a_1", "label": "Answer 1", "default": "Completely normal, and actually a good sign - it means they are engaging with it. Keep placing it back down. Every throw-and-retrieve is a motor skills workout. Consistency is key." },
        { "type": "text", "id": "q_2", "label": "Question 2", "default": "When should I move to the toddler cutlery?" },
        { "type": "textarea", "id": "a_2", "label": "Answer 2", "default": "Around 12 months is a good guide, but follow your child's lead. When they are confidently picking up the baby cutlery and making attempts to feed themselves, they are ready to progress." },
        { "type": "text", "id": "q_3", "label": "Question 3", "default": "Do I need to teach my child how to hold the handle?" },
        { "type": "textarea", "id": "a_3", "label": "Answer 3", "default": "No - that is the whole point of the design. The ergonomic shape naturally encourages the correct grip. Trust the product. Over-correcting can reduce confidence and slow progress." },
        { "type": "text", "id": "q_4", "label": "Question 4", "default": "When can I remove the suction from the bowl?" },
        { "type": "textarea", "id": "a_4", "label": "Answer 4", "default": "When your toddler is not constantly sweeping the bowl off the tray, try the non-slip base. You can switch back any time. Some meals or environments still benefit from suction even at 2 years old." },
        { "type": "text", "id": "q_5", "label": "Question 5", "default": "Is the toddler knife really safe?" },
        { "type": "textarea", "id": "a_5", "label": "Answer 5", "default": "Yes. The doddl toddler knife has a specially designed blade that can cut soft foods but is safe for small hands. The handle teaches the downward push motion, not a sawing motion." },
        { "type": "text", "id": "q_6", "label": "Question 6", "default": "My child is 3 and still struggling. Should I be worried?" },
        { "type": "textarea", "id": "a_6", "label": "Answer 6", "default": "Every child develops at their own pace. The doddl set is used by occupational therapists with children who have developmental delays. If you have specific concerns, we always recommend speaking to your health visitor or GP." }
      ]
